{{main article|Religion in Cuba}}
In August 1960, several bishops signed a joint pastoral letter condemning communism and declaring it incompatible with Catholicism, and calling on Catholics to reject it.<ref name="Mallin1994">{{cite book|author=Jay Mallin|title=Covering Castro: Rise and Decline of Cuba's Communist Dictator|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TUGwuKQWXW8C|date=1 January 1994|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-2053-0}}</ref> Castro gave a four-hour speech the next day, condemning priests who serve "great wealth" and using fears of [[Falangism in Latin America|Falangist]] influence to attack Spanish born priests, declaring "There is no doubt that [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] has a sizeable group of fascist priests in Cuba."

Originally more tolerant of religion, [[Cuba]] began arresting many believers and shutting down religious schools after the [[Bay of Pigs invasion]]. In 1961 The Cuban government confiscated Catholic schools, including the Jesuit school Fidel Castro had attended. In 1965 it exiled two hundred priests.<ref name=buckley2005-11-21>William F. Buckley Jr., [http://old.nationalreview.com/flashback/1998200511210830.asp Cuba libre?], November 21, 2005, National review.</ref>

In 1976 the [[Constitution of Cuba]] added a clause stating that the "socialist state...bases its activity on, and educates the people in, the scientific materialist concept of the universe". In
1992, the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union]] lead the country to declare itself a [[secular state]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.state.gov/documents/organization/193177.pdf|title=CUBA - Status of Government Respect for Religious Freedom|work=International Religious Freedom Report for 2011|publisher=United States Department of State - Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Constitution of Cuba, Article 8: Freedom of Religion and Separation of Church and State|url=http://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/quotes/constitution-of-cuba-article-8-freedom-of-religion-and-separation-of-church-and-state|publisher=Berkley Center for Religion, Peace & World Affairs}}</ref> and Catholic groups have worked to advance the [[United States–Cuban Thaw|Cuban thaw]]. In January 1998, [[Pope John Paul II]] paid a historic visit to the island, invited by the Cuban government and the Catholic Church in Cuba. The pope criticized the US embargo during his visit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/12/17/catholic-church-cuba-us_n_6344510.html|title=How Pope John Paul II Paved The Way For The U.S.-Cuba Thaw|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref> [[Pope Benedict XVI]] visited Cuba in 2012 and [[Pope Francis]] visited in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/with-clean-streets-and-a-bit-of-suspense-cuba-awaits-pope-francis/2015/09/19/ee4a5ba6-5bf5-11e5-8475-781cc9851652_story.html|title=Pope Francis arrives in Havana, praising U.S.-Cuba thaw|author=Nick Miroff|date=19 September 2015|work=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/10/pope-meets-cuban-president-raul-castro|title=Castro thanks Pope Francis for brokering thaw between Cuba and US|author=Rosie Scammell|work=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/americas/breakthrough-on-cuba-highlights-popes-role-as-diplomatic-broker.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-pope-francis-us-cuba-talks-20141218-story.html|title=Pope Francis' role in Cuba stretches back years|author=Los Angeles Times|date=18 December 2014|work=latimes.com}}</ref>

===North Korea===
